OBJECTIVE: To help medical students learn about Aboriginal culture and health by 
introducing them to Aboriginal people living in rural and remote areas.
SETTING: A seven-day field trip to Aboriginal communities and local health 
services in the eastern Goldfields Region of Western Australia.
METHODS: Students interviewed local Aboriginal people, and representatives of 
community organisations and health service providers, and supplemented this 
information with their own field observations. The field research was used in 
completing three community health projects: one on infant health, another on 
environmental health, and a third on general beliefs of Aboriginal people about 
health and disease, prevention and treatment, and traditional and Western 
medicine.
