155. Gerontologist. 1995 Oct;35(5):588-96. doi: 10.1093/geront/35.5.588.

Sex mortality differentials and selective survival in large medfly cohorts: 
implications for human sex mortality differentials.

Carey JR(1), Liedo P.

Author information:
(1)Department of Entomology, University of California, Davis 95616, USA.

Experimental studies on male-female mortality differences in nonhuman species 
are important because they provide insights into both the nature of age-specific 
gender differences and the concept of selective survival--whether one subgroup 
in a population (e.g., males) is consistently more frail than another subgroup 
(e.g., females). We found that it was not possible to classify either sex as 
more robust or longer lived since relative longevity was conditional on age 
(young or old), cage conditions (solitary confinement or grouped cages), and 
treatment (starvation, irradiation, or density). Implications of these findings 
are discussed including selective survival, demographic selection, a framework 
for male-female mortality differentials, and an evolutionary perspective on 
gender differences in longevity.

